"Full-time equivalent enrollment" means the sum of:
The number of students enrolled in grades 1 through 12 or their equivalent in regular day school programs on September 30 of the previous school year;
Except as provided in item (iii) of this paragraph, the product of the number of students enrolled in kindergarten programs on September 30 of the prior school year and:
0.60 in fiscal year 2004;
0.70 in fiscal year 2005;
0.80 in fiscal year 2006;
0.90 in fiscal year 2007; and
1.00 in fiscal year 2008 and each fiscal year thereafter;
In Garrett County, the number of students enrolled in kindergarten programs on September 30 of the prior school year; and
The number of full-time equivalent students, as determined by a regulation of the Department, enrolled in evening high school programs during the previous school year.

"Local contribution rate" means the figure that is calculated as follows:
Multiply the statewide full-time equivalent enrollment by $624, and multiply this product by:
0.46 in fiscal year 2004;
0.47 in fiscal year 2005;
0.48 in fiscal year 2006;
0.49 in fiscal year 2007; and
0.50 in fiscal year 2008 and each fiscal year thereafter;
Multiply the statewide full-time equivalent enrollment by the amount that the annual per pupil foundation amount exceeds $624, and multiply this product by 0.50;
Add the two products calculated in items (i) and (ii) of this paragraph, and divide the resulting sum by the sum of the wealth of all of the counties in this State; and
Round the result obtained in item (iii) of this paragraph to seven decimal places and express as a percent with five decimal places.

"State share of the foundation program" means the greater of:
The difference between the foundation program and the local share of the foundation program; and
The result obtained by multiplying the annual per pupil foundation amount by the county's full-time equivalent enrollment, and multiplying this product by:
0.25 in fiscal year 2004;
0.24 in fiscal year 2005;
0.22 in fiscal year 2006;
0.19 in fiscal year 2007; and
0.15 in fiscal year 2008 and each fiscal year thereafter.

"Wealth" means the sum of:
Net taxable income;
100 percent of the assessed value of the operating real property of public utilities;
40 percent of the assessed valuation of all other real property; and
50 percent of assessed value of personal property.

Qualifying nonrecurring costs, as defined in regulations adopted by the State Board, shall include but are not limited to:
Computer laboratories;
Technology enhancement;
New instructional program start-up costs; and
Books other than classroom textbooks.

Except as provided in paragraph (9) of this subsection, when considering whether to grant a county's waiver request, the State Board shall consider the following factors:
External environmental factors such as a loss of a major employer or industry affecting a county or a broad economic downturn affecting more than one county;
A county's tax base;
Rate of inflation relative to growth of student population in a county;
Maintenance of effort requirement relative to a county's statutory ability to raise revenues;
A county's history of exceeding the required maintenance of effort amount under paragraph (1)(ii) of this subsection;
An agreement between a county and a county board that a waiver should be granted;
Significant reductions in State aid to a county and municipalities of the county for the fiscal year for which a waiver is requested;
The number of waivers a county has received in the past 5 years; and
The history of compensation adjustments for employees of the county board and county government.

When considering whether to grant a county's waiver request under this paragraph, the State Board shall consider the following factors:
Whether a county has submitted sufficient evidence that the factors in paragraph (8)(v) of this subsection will affect a county's ongoing ability to meet the maintenance of effort requirement;
Whether a county is at its maximum taxing authority under the law;
Whether a county's education appropriation is commensurate with a county's wealth;
Whether a county's history of exceeding the required maintenance of effort has made meeting the maintenance of effort requirement in future years unsustainable; and
Whether a county has received a rebasing waiver in the past 5 years.

In this subsection, "State financial assistance for public education" means the total financial assistance provided by the State to a county board under the following programs:
Funding for the foundation program under this section;
In fiscal year 2009, 50% of the funding received under the GCEI adjustment grant program under subsection (f) of this section and in fiscal year 2010, 60% of the funding received under the GCEI adjustment grant program under subsection (f) of this section;
Transportation aid under § 5-205 of this subtitle;
Funding for compensatory education under § 5-207 of this subtitle;
Funding for students with limited English proficiency under § 5-208 of this subtitle;
Funding for special education students under § 5-209 of this subtitle;
Funding for the guaranteed tax base program under § 5-210 of this subtitle;
50% of the State payments for retirement contributions for employees of a local school system in accordance with the provisions of Division II of the State Personnel and Pensions Article; and
Funding for supplemental grants under this subsection.

In this subsection, "GCEI adjustment" means the foundation program for each county multiplied by:
0.000 in Allegany;
0.018 in Anne Arundel;
0.042 in Baltimore City;
0.008 in Baltimore;
0.021 in Calvert;
0.000 in Caroline;
0.014 in Carroll;
0.000 in Cecil;
0.020 in Charles;
0.000 in Dorchester;
0.024 in Frederick;
0.000 in Garrett;
0.000 in Harford;
0.015 in Howard;
0.010 in Kent;
0.034 in Montgomery;
0.048 in Prince George's;
0.011 in Queen Anne's;
0.002 in St. Mary's;
0.000 in Somerset;
0.000 in Talbot;
0.000 in Washington;
0.000 in Wicomico; and
0.000 in Worcester.

Subject to paragraph (4) of this subsection, the amount of the grant to each county board under this subsection shall equal the GCEI adjustment for the county board multiplied times:
0.50 in fiscal year 2006;
0.62 in fiscal year 2007;
0.74 in fiscal year 2008;
0.86 in fiscal year 2009; and
1.00 in fiscal year 2010 and each fiscal year thereafter.

In this subsection, "total direct education aid" means the total financial assistance provided by the State to a county board under the following programs:
Funding for the foundation program including funds for the Geographic Cost of Education under this section;
Transportation aid under § 5-205 of this subtitle;
Funding for compensatory education under § 5-207 of this subtitle;
Funding for students with limited English proficiency under § 5-208 of this subtitle;
Funding for special education students under § 5-209 of this subtitle;
Funding for the guaranteed tax base program under § 5-210 of this subtitle; and
Funding for grants provided under this subsection.
